title: For Sale:  Ruger .44 Magnum Carbine Custom
postcontent: This is a nice one.  Classic Ruger .44 Magnum Carbine with a custom stock by Fajen and topped off with some vintage Japanese glass in the form of a  very nice 4x32 "TV" view scope.  This carbine does have some minor scratches and slight dings as you would expect of a rifle of this vintage.  The action is tight and works perfectly and the rifling is clear and sharp.  It's a very fun rifle to shoot too.   As you will notice, there is no barrel band, this stock was designed this way by Fajen.  The action and barrel "float" in the stock and are retained only by the recoil block bolt.  This is a beautiful and functional classic carbine that is completly unique, a "one of a kind".  Now in case you don't know mluch about Ruger .44 Carbines, they are somewhat rare as Ruger did not make to many, and didn't make them for very long either.  This one has an intergral tubular magazine which holds 4 rounds of .44 magnum ammuntion (five if you put one in the chamber) and as I said, it's fun to shoot.  Accurate too.  Anyway, that is my custom Ruger Carbine, and if your interested in owning this great little rifle, let me know.  I also have many more pictures if you want to see more.  Thanks.NOTICE:  I DO NOT HAVE THE ORIGINAL STOCK FOR THIS RIFLE.  People have been contacting me and asking if I do, to save time I have added this to the ad.  If you need a stock, try Numrich Gun Parts, they have them.  Thanks.

title: For Sale:  RWS 350 in .177 w/ Scope
postcontent: For sale I have an almost new RWS 350 in .177.  Only has about 100 pellets through it.  There is absolutley nothing wrong with this rifle, I just have too many airguns and need to get rid of a few.  I have only had this one a few months.   I bought it NIB because I got a great deal, even though I wasn't in the market for another.  I shot it once, and did some chrony testing, and I have to tell you , this thing is an absolute beast.  It's the most powerfull .177 I've ever had, and I own 3 RWS 48s.  I don't recall the exact numbers or pellet weight, but this rifle was hitting just over 21 ft/lbs with a couple different pellets.  If you know anything about air rifles, you'll know that is a lot of energy for a .177.  My 48s are considered very powerful, and they only put out about 17-18ft/lbs in .177.  This gun is not a toy!  It is also heavy and may be a bit of a challenge for some to cock.  I'm not a really big guy or anything, and it wasn't a problem for me, but if you're older or have a handicap it might be a challenge. Gun comes in original box, and I also have a very nice UTG mount and UTG scope (3-9 40mm). This gun has a tremendous amount of recoil, and the UTG mount is one of the few that will stand up to it.  I shot about 80 of the pellets with the scope mounted, and it hasn't budged.   I only plinked with it, and didn't try to shoot any tight groups or anything, but I can tell you I hit everthing I aimed at.  Guns this powerful can be a challenge to print, but this is also part of the appeal for some (like me). You have to practice and know your rilfe to shoot tight groups with a powerful springer like this.On weekends we could meet in Indianola, during the week we could meet in Des Moines.   At this time I WILL NOT SHIP.  I am firm on price.   I will throw in some free pellets as well.  Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  1863 U.S. Springfield Rifle Musket "Civil War"
postcontent: This U.S. Model 1863 Rifle Musket was manufactured by Springfield Armory in 1864. The lock plate is dated "1863" behind the hammer and the top of the barrel is dated "1864". The lock plate is roll-stamped with the Springfield Armory Eagle/Shield motif in front of the hammer followed by "U.S./SPRINGFIELD" in two lines. A small Eagle/Shield motif is stamped on the face of the percussion nipple bolster. A two-initial Sub-inspection mark is stamped on the left side of the stock behind the trigger guard. The Model 1863 Type I Rifle Musket combined features of the Model 1861 Special Rifle Musket and the Model 1861 Rifle Musket and was the standard Federal infantry long arm during the last two years of the Civil War. This 1863 Rifle is in excellent condition with all working parts and would make a GREAT addition to any collection. A U.S. Model 1863 Musket in this condition appraises for more than $2500.00 book value so take advantage of the low asking price and if you have any questions, please ask.
